 the level of supervision.</p>\n\n<p>You may be able to get help with fees or a discount if you&rsquo;re on certain benefits or a low income.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.justice.gov.uk/downloads/forms/opg/opg120-fee-guide.pdf\" title=\"Download 'Deputyship fees' guidance (PDF, 309KB\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Deputyship fees’ guidance (PDF, 309KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/become-deputy/cancel-or-end-deputys-responsibilities","slug":"cancel-or-end-deputys-responsibilities","order":5,"title":"Cancel or end a deputy's responsibilities","body":"<p>A deputy&rsquo;s role can end or be cancelled for a number of reasons.</p>\n\n<h2>The court order expires</h2>\n\n<p>If the court order expires, the deputy can reapply to the Court of Protection.</p>\n\n<p>A new deputy can also apply for the role.</p>\n\n<h2>The Court of Protection ends the deputy&rsquo;s role</h2>\n\n<p>This can happen if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>the deputy hasn&rsquo;t been acting in the person&rsquo;s best interest</li>\n  <li>the person no longer needs the deputy&rsquo;s help</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>In the first case, the Court of Protection will appoint a new deputy.</p>\n\n<h2>The person who needs a deputy dies</h2>\n\n<p>If this happens, the deputy must tell the Office of the Public Guardian as soon as possible.</p>\n\n<p>They may have to provide a final report about their decisions and financial transactions.</p>\n\n<h2>The deputy dies</h2>\n\n<p>If the deputy dies and the person still needs someone to act on their behalf, the Court of Protection will appoint a new deputy.</p>\n\n<p>The court can appoint a panel deputy if no one applies for the role.</p>\n"}]},"tags":[{"title":"Lasting Power of Attorney, being in care and your financial affairs","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/births-deaths-marriages%2Flasting-power-attorney.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes dealing with benefits, taxes and leaving care","short_description":nu